      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You should repot your fiddle leaf fig into a fresh, well-draining potting mix specifically designed for houseplants or a blend of peat moss, perlite, and orchid bark. To avoid killing it, gently loosen the existing soil, carefully remove the plant, and trim any tangled or dead roots with clean shears before placing it in the new pot with ample space. Once the roots are spread out and covered with fresh soil, water thoroughly but ensure the pot has drainage holes to prevent root rot.\n\nIf you're worried about the process, you can also consider a \"top-down\" repotting where you only add a layer of soil at the bottom first, gradually adding more as you work the plant in. This method minimizes root disturbance and reduces transplant shock. Just be mindful of your plant's water needs and avoid overwatering during the initial weeks after repotting.\n\nRemember, fiddle leaf figs prefer slightly acidic soil with a pH between 5.5 and 6.5. If you're unsure about the exact soil composition, look for mixes labeled for \"difficult-to-grow\" plants or tropical foliage, as these often contain the right balance of nutrients and drainage. Good luck with your",
